## 2. THEORETICAL FOUNDATIONS

### Core references:
The following works form the standard reference base for DSR in Information Systems.
A thesis should draw on these where applicable and justify its methodological framing
explicitly. They are not mandatory in a universal sense, but in practice most
rigorous DSR theses will reference them.

| Reference | What it contributes |
|---|---|
| Hevner et al. (2004) | The seven guidelines for DSR; the foundational reference |
| Hevner (2007) | The three-cycle model (Relevance, Design, Rigor) |
| Peffers et al. (2007) | The DSRM process model with six activities |
| Gregor & Hevner (2013) | How DSR contributions are classified and communicated |
| March & Smith (1995) | Artifact types: constructs, models, methods, instantiations |
| Venable et al. (2016) | FEDS: Framework for Evaluation in Design Science Research |
| Gregor & Jones (2007) | The anatomy of a design theory |
