## 11. THE SEVEN GUIDELINES (HEVNER ET AL., 2004)

Every DSR thesis must address these guidelines. They serve as both a design framework
and an examiner checklist.

| Guideline | What it requires | Common failure |
|---|---|---|
| **G1: Design as artifact** | A concrete, evaluable artifact must be produced | Artifact type undefined or unclear |
| **G2: Problem relevance** | The problem must be practically important | Relevance only asserted, not evidenced |
| **G3: Design evaluation** | The artifact must be rigorously evaluated | Evaluation too brief or exclusively positive |
| **G4: Research contributions** | New knowledge produced (artifact, method, theory) | Contribution not explicitly stated |
| **G5: Research rigor** | Rigorous methods in both development and evaluation | Method selection unjustified |
| **G6: Design as a search process** | Iterative process, not a one-shot solution | No iteration evidence |
| **G7: Communication of research** | Results communicated to both researchers and practitioners | Discussion chapter absent or underdeveloped |

